  "prompt": "How do you know you're over your relationship?",
  "response": "Getting over a relationship is a personal and often complex journey. Here are some signs that you might be moving on:\n\n1. **Emotional Stability:** You no longer feel intense emotional swings when you think about your ex. Feelings of sadness, anger, or longing have diminished significantly.\n\n2. **Acceptance:** You have accepted the end of the relationship and no longer wish for things to go back to how they were. You understand why the relationship ended and have come to terms with it.\n\n3. **Reduced Thoughts:** Your ex is no longer constantly on your mind. You can go days or even weeks without thinking about them, and when you do, it\u2019s brief and not distressing.\n\n4. **No More Obsessive Behaviors:** You\u2019ve stopped checking their social media, asking friends about them, or trying to find out what they\u2019re up to.\n\n5. **Interest in New Relationships:** You feel open to meeting new people and potentially starting a new relationship. You\u2019re excited about the possibilities of new connections.\n\n6. **Reclaiming Your Identity:** You\u2019ve rediscovered your interests, hobbies, and goals outside of the relationship. You\u2019re focusing on personal growth and enjoying activities that make you happy.\n\n7. **Positive Outlook:** You have a hopeful and positive outlook on the future. You believe that you can find happiness and fulfillment, whether single or in a new relationship.\n\n8. **Physical Signs:** You\u2019re sleeping well, eating normally, and taking care of your health. Your body is no longer showing signs of stress related to the breakup.\n\n9. **Social Engagement:** You\u2019re enjoying spending time with friends and family, and you feel comfortable and happy in social situations.\n\n10. **Forgiveness:** You\u2019ve forgiven your ex and yourself for any mistakes made during the relationship. You\u2019re no longer holding onto resentment or grudges.\n\nEveryone\u2019s healing process is different, and it\u2019s important to be patient with yourself. If you\u2019re still struggling, it might be helpful to talk to a therapist or counselor who can provide guidance and support.",
